  "prompt": "My interview in IOCL lasted for 30 minutes but the interview was below average.What are my chances of getting selected?",
  "response": "It's difficult to predict your chances of getting selected based solely on the duration and your perception of the interview's quality. Here are a few factors to consider:\n\n1. **Interview Performance**: If you felt that the interview was below average, it's possible that the interviewers may have noticed this as well. However, interviewers often consider various aspects beyond just the content, such as enthusiasm, problem-solving ability, and cultural fit.\n\n2. **Competition**: The selection process can be highly competitive. Your performance relative to other candidates is a significant factor. If other candidates performed exceptionally well, that could affect your chances regardless of your own performance.\n\n3. **Overall Application**: Your academic background, relevant experience, and any other application materials may still work in your favor even if the interview didn't go as well as you hoped.\n\n4. **Interviewer Expectations**: Sometimes, an interview might feel less engaging due to the interviewer's style or expectations. If the interviewers didn't ask you many questions or seem interested, it may not fully reflect your capabilities.\n\n5. **Feedback Loop**: It's normal to feel uncertain after an interview. Consider reaching out for feedback if that\u2019s an option, or reflect on which areas you felt were lacking to improve for future opportunities.\n\nUltimately, while a 30-minute interview might feel short and below average, it's just one part of the selection process. Give yourself some time to see how the process unfolds. Good luck!",
